<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_04.gif"><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/clear.gif" height=35 width=1></td>
<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> A Walk Through The Mines of Moria, 1<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.22)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=8714'>Xanthix "Xanthix" Xanthix</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=8714&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> February 24, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Let&#39;s take a look at some of the new cards from the Mines of Moria expansion. It seems like there hasn&#39;t been that much discussion of how the new cards will affect the current LOTR environment, so I&#39;d like to look at a few cards and make some predictions. This is the first article in what may become a series (if people like it!). Hopefully this will spark some thought or discussion, so that when MoM doeshimmer, we can all be ready to enter the Mines!<br>
<br>
First of all, let&#39;s take a look at the most anticipated card from MoM, the Balrog. I chose this version because everyone&#39;s seen the common Balrog for some time now.<br>
<br>
	?The Balrog: Flame of Udûn<br>
	[Moria] Minion (Cost 14)<br>
	17 Strength, 5 Vitality, Home 4<br>
	Damage +1. Fierce.<br>
	To play, spot a [Moria] Orc. Discard The Balrog if not underground.<br>
	Shadow: Exert The Balrog and remove 2 to play a [Moria] Orc from<br>
	your discard pile.<br>
	&quot;...suddenly it drew itself up to a great height,<br>
	and its wings were spread from wall to wall...&quot;<br>
<br>
Wow. This card is awesome. First of all, it&#39;s just visually stunning; I&#39;d play it just so I could look at it some more! Kudos to Decipher for continuing their tradition of cool-looking cards.<br>
<br>
Then you come to the Balrog&#39;s stats. 17 strength is of course huge - don&#39;t let this guy skirmish a Hobbit! The Balrog can overwhelm any companion (except rare Boromir, which requires using the Balrog&#39;s sword and whip), or should we say any two companions, since it&#39;s fierce? High vitality also protects it from directed archery and allows it to use its weapon&#39;s special abilities liberally.<br>
<br>
I&#39;m sure this card will see play in some Moria decks (due to the spotting requirement). However, even though site 5 and Goblin Runners make the Balrog easier to play, using the Balrog will probably spend all the twilight, hurting Moria&#39;s ability to drop tons of goblins. Also, I don&#39;t see much use for the Balrog&#39;s goblin-resurrecting ability: How much twilight are you going to have after playing this bad boy? Finally, you&#39;ll only be able to use the Balrog for a turn, since no current site 6 is underground. If you had a Swarms deck, would you want to spend all the twilight on a Balrog that might just eat 2 Hobbit Stealths, and then get discarded as the fellowship moves to a sanctuary? Or would you rather play your 12 Goblins with weapons?<br>
<br>
Unless MoM&#39;s site &quot;Great Chasm&quot; is an underground site 6, in which case playing a site 5 Balrog would force the party to stop, I think this card won&#39;t see much tournament play. Lots of casual play of course, I mean just look at the card, it&#39;s a fricken&#39; Force of Nature or Phyrexian Dreadnought! But for tournament play, I would be much more afraid of a Durin&#39;s Bane Balrog from a Sauron or Uruk-hai deck.<br>
<br>
<br>
And now, an equally-eagerly-expected free people&#39;s card:<br>
<br>
	?Gandalf&#39;s Staff<br>
	[Gandalf] Artifact - Staff (Cost 2)<br>
	+1 Vitality<br>
	Bearer must be Gandalf.<br>
	the twilight cost of each [Gandalf] spell is -1.<br>
	Skirmish: Exert Gandalf twice to cancel a skirmish involving him.<br>
	&quot;As the wizard passed on ahead up the great steps, he held<br>
	his staff aloft, and from its tip there came a faint radiance.&quot;<br>
<br>
This one is easy to predict: it&#39;s sure to be included in just about every Gandalf deck out there! Lemme see, for 2 twilight, Gandalf is vitality 5 and can cancel skirmishes at will? Not to mention that it pays for itself by reducing spell costs by 1, and can be used for cards like Staff Asunder and You Cannot Pass. Gandalf becomes a real powerhouse with these MoM cards.<br>
<br>
I also think this card will be preferred to Wizard&#39;s Staff: that gives a strength bonus and lets you achieve Servant Of The Secret Fire&#39;s effect for 2 exertions, but the +1 vitality is very valuable, and lowering Gandalf&#39;s spell&#39;s costs is as good as No Stranger to the Shadows. Of course, you can always switch staffs (staves?) by using Staff Asunder!<br>
<br>
I can see a lot of synergy developing with Gandalf cards, and I might predict a new all-Gandalf type deck. Picture this: Gandalf starts, finds his Cart and his buddy Butterbur. He gets a strength boost from Glamdring and 5 vitality from his staff (I wonder what Shadowfax will give him?). He can boost strength (Mysterious Wizard), help others (Secret Fire), and cancel skirmishes right and left. His staff reduces the cost of these spells, and Strength of Spirit keeps wounds off of him. Butterbur even fetches copies of his spells, and he keeps extra staffs in his Cart. Sheesh, why not give him a bow and officially retire the other fellowship members?<br>
<br>
<br>
